 首波暴力式情歌 You’ll never know  MV一定要看到最後！  
8ID團隊執導突破性新型態MV，讓人情緒緊繃到一口氣看完才敢呼吸！

首波主打You’ll never know是台灣少見的Future R&B暴力式情歌，這首歌是J.Sheon自己的全創作，歌詞描述關於感情中，那個讓你想要跨越朋友界線的女孩，那種內心深藏激烈情感想要守護著對方的心境。直白的文字，加上難以估計的殺傷力，雖然是一首備胎情歌，編曲內藏的激烈情感與嘶吼般宣泄的唱腔，讓這首暴力式情歌跨過兩個人的界線，成為三個人的結界。

這支MV請來台灣超強視覺團隊8ID執導，使用特殊拍攝手法，在同個時空及同個場景以多支線進行式的方式呈現，將歌曲整體滿溢的緊繃情緒，緊密的與畫面結合，讓人幾乎一口氣看完才敢呼吸，是一種突破性的新形態MV；這次MV還特別邀請J.Sheon的師妹，擁有網路超高人氣的個性女生—孫尤安來擔當女主角演出，為這首歌賦予更具張力性的色彩，MV並暗藏驚人的超展開結局，一定要看到最後！因為在愛情裡，你永遠不會知道，誰才是傷人的那一方。

caption: false
description:
'Mengertilah Cinta' adalah lagu yang disusun Iman (vokal) dan Wima (bass). Lagu ini diciptakan sekitar 8 tahun lalu yang kemudian disempurnakan kembali ketika J-Rocks mempersiapkan albumnya dan akhirnya dirilis pada akhir 2017. 
Seperti kebanyakan lagu-lagu di album keempatnya itu, J-Rocks memasukkan banyak warna baru di dalam musiknya. Bagi pelantun hits ‘Lepaskan Diriku’ tersebut lagu ini  adalah salah satu hasil perjalanan bermusik mereka yang cukup panjang. 

"Lagu ini benar-benar bentuk pendewasaan J-Rocks yang dibalut orkestra sungguhan. Kita bekerjasama dengan komposer yang canggih banget yaitu Andi Rianto. Memang konsepnya kami ingin membuat komposisi yang grande, yang megah," ujar Iman. 
Benar saja, denting piano dan megahnya string session di 'Mengertilah Cinta' sudah bisa didengar sejak awal lagu. Keduanya bersahutan sempurna hingga menuju klimak dan menutupnya dengan manis. 

"Single ketiga ini bercerita tentang seseorang yang ingin dimengerti tapi nggak bisa mengutarakan apa yang ada di hatinya. Ini dari sisi cowok ya, bisa juga dari sisi cewek dan bisa jadi beda. Tentang permasalahan pasangan yang salah paham karena beda sudut pandang," jelas Iman yang menulis lirik 'Mengertilah Cinta'. 

'Mengertilah Cinta' sedikit mengingatkan kita akan musik-musik awal munculnya J-Rocks di awal 2000-an. Nuansa dan benang merah dari karya-karya lawas mereka terdengar sayup-sayup dengan penyempurnaan perkembangan bermusik Iman, Wima, Anton (drum) dan juga Sony (gitar). Sementara itu keempatnya kompak menyerahkan penilaian lagu baru mereka kepada penggemar saja. 

"Coba dengerin lagu ini dengan seksama, pejamkan mata, resapi dan bayangkan semua kata-kata dari liriknya seolah kita yang bicara," pesan Iman. 

Mungkin ini bukan kali pertamanya J-Rocks membuat video klip di Jepang, tapi untuk single ‘Mengertilah Cinta’ menorehkan kisah seru juga sebuah petualangan.  Mereka mengambil lokasi video klip di kawasan Shirakawa-go, Honsu, Jepang. Daerah tersebut adalah sebuah lokasi pedesaan yang dikelilingi pegunungan. Tepat ketika salju sedang menghujani kawasan tersebut, J-Rocks pun tak menyiakan kesempatan untuk syuting di lokasi walau hanya punya waktu dua jam saja. Untuk mencapai lokasi tersebut pun tidaklah mudah.

▶ Penyanyi: J-Rocks 
▶Judul: Mengertilah Cinta 
▶Directed by: Angling Sagaran
▶Composer: Iman / Wima 
▶Lirik: Iman 
▶Produser & Penata Musik: Andi Rianto & J-Rocks 
▶String Arrangement : Andi Rianto
▶Mixing Engineer: Roedra at Aquarius Pondok Indah Studio
▶Mastering Engineer: Steve Mart at Studio 301 Sydney.
▶Publisher: PT Aquarius Pustaka Musik 
▶Produksi: PT Aquarius Musikindo 
▶Managemen & Promosi: J-Rocks & Aquarius 

Listen on:
▶Apple Music: https://apple.co/2DL4NTk
▶iTunes : https://apple.co/2NOyJCo
▶Spotify : https://spoti.fi/2DzxBha

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
‘Mengertilah Cinta’ is a song composed by Iman (vocals) and Wima (bass). It was composed around 8 years ago, and was polished off when J-Rocks prepared and released their album at the end of 2017.  As with most songs in this fourth album, J-Rocks added new colors in their music. For the band popular for their hits ‘Lepaskan Diriku’, this song is one of the results of their quite long journey.  

“This song is truly a representation of J-Rocks reaching maturity, accompanied by a real orchestra. We worked with a highly skilled composer, Andi Rianto. The concept was to create a grand, magnificent composition,” explained Iman.  

The clink of the piano keys and the grandness of the string section in ‘Mengertilah Cinta’ can be felt from the beginning of the song. They both perfectly respond to each other towards the climax, ending the song sweetly.  

“This third single tells of someone who wants to be understood but cannot express what is in his heart. This is from a boy’s perspective, but it could also be from a girl’s perspective and could also differ. About the problems of couples who misunderstand due to different points of view,” continues Iman about the lyrics of ‘Mengertilah Cinta’. 

‘Mengertilah Cinta’ slightly reminds us of the music from J-Rocks debut in the early 2000s. The nuances and common themes of their earlier work can be felt with the maturing musical skills of Iman, Wima, Anton (drums) and Sony (guitars). Meanwhile, they all agree to let their fans judge the song for themselves.  
 
This might not be the first time that J-Rocks shot a video in Japan, but the process of ‘Mengertilah Cinta’ came with great stories and adventure.  They chose to shoot the music video at the Shirakawa-go area, Honshu, Japan. This area is a village surrounded by mountains. Just when snow started to fall, J-Rocks did not miss their chance to shoot on location, despite only having two hours. It was not easy even to reach the location.

caption: false
description:
Bob Boilen | April 24, 2017 — As the primary booker of the Tiny Desk Concerts, I have this self-imposed rule: No artist can come back for a second visit unless there's something wholly different about what they're doing. The first time alt-J played the Tiny Desk, in 2012, they came as a four-piece; electric guitar, bass, keyboards and drums. They were a pretty new band, their album had been out a few months and they were playing in clubs for a couple hundred people, not much more.

In the five years since the band visited it has found quite a few new fans. When I heard cuts from the newest album Relaxer a few months ago I flipped and tried to think of a way to bring them back. So I wrote them, saying I'd love to have them again but that it would have to be wholly, out-of-the-box different. I told them I'd hire a brass band, an African kora player if need be, a string section... They took up the challenge. They told me to find a cellist and two violinists.

I wrote to my friend Carol Anne Bosco, a cellist, who turned out to be a huge fan of the band and helped find two violinists for the performance. About four days before the performance the band sent the string parts, written by their friend Will Gardner.

On Monday morning, the English band met the American string players and they all gathered behind my desk. As they worked their way through a first pass at "Three Worn Words," I noticed them and relieved — alt-J had actually never heard the string arrangements, this was the first time. They sounded beautiful. By noon, NPR employees and friends gathered around my desk to witness this astonishing concert from alt-J, including two new songs and two old favorites. Magic.

Relaxer is available for pre-order now:
iTunes: https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/relaxer/id1209198388
Amazon: https://www.amazon.com/Relaxer-Alt-J/dp/B06XH2QX1D

caption: false
description:
There's mystery in the music of Alt-J: The band's songs are wrapped in enigmatic textures, with swift shifts in arrangements inside every song and an oddness to the drums. Mere glimpses of lyrics are discernible, even after listening over and over — and if you can decipher the words, the meanings don't necessarily follow immediately. Still, those words reside at the core of Alt-J, and they're cinematic and stunning and sometimes brutal.

Seeing Alt-J live in concert — or here at the Tiny Desk — reveals a few of those mysteries, making a band that can be difficult on first listen a bit easier to digest. For one, seeing Joe Newman sing makes his words less oblique; for another, that curious rhythm at the foundation of the songs reveals not a hint of cymbals. And, though the drums are stripped down more than ever at the Tiny Desk, they still provide the essence of an original sound. Thom Green plays mostly with a mounted tambourine and cowbell for the sorts of things a hi-hat would accomplish — that tick tick sound, with the snap of the sound coming from a small-bodied 10" snare called a popcorn snare. The sparseness that happens in the absence of crashing cymbals leaves a lot of space in the music.

Alt-J is from Leeds, England — home to another of my favorite art-rock bands, Gang of Four. Both play angular, poetic music that takes unexpected turns, shifting gears when you least expect it. Alt-J made my favorite album of 2012, An Awesome Wave, and if you're new to the group, the understated sound may get lost on you at first. But listen to the words and study how the songs evolve: No one else is making music like this. This is an original, innovative band with a brilliant present and a brighter future. --BOB BOILEN

Set List
"Tessellate"
"Something Good"
"Matilda"

Credits
Producer: Bob Boilen; Editor: Denise DeBelius; Audio Engineers: Kevin Wait, Suraya Mohamed; Videographers: Denise DeBelius, Christopher Parks, Ryan Smith; photo by Lauren Rock/NPR
title: Alt-J: NPR Music Tiny Desk Concert

The acclaimed international vocalist has performed solo and with her live band all across the globe including the Caribbean, Norway, Romania, Dubai, Cyprus, France, Turkey, Dominican Republic and Spain. Along with her busy theatre tour, One Night of Adele, she regularly works for clients including P&O on their flagship cruise liners, Sheraton Hotels, Hilton Hotels, Lancaster London Hotel, The Dorchester, NSPCC, The Mall of the Emirates, Red Bull Formula One, Dyson, Honda, Celtic Manor Resort and In July 2017 she is even booked to support the Royal Philharmonic Concert Orchestra!
